v.s: Last week I went to the theatre.
What did you do after the play?
I didn't go home. I went for a long walk in the park.
What did you do after the park?
I went down to the river and I sat down to have my picnic lunch.
Picnic lunch! That's interesting. Did you enjoy it?
Yes, I like picnics very much. They're very relaxing.
Where did you go for your picnic?
I didn't go anywhere. I had my picnic in the park.
In the park! That's funny. You had a picnic in the park before lunch and a picnic in the park after lunch!
I know. It was fun. By the way, did you go to the cinema last weekend?
No, I usually rest at home on Sundays. I watch television or read books.
What do you do on Sunday evenings?
I don't go out on Sunday evenings. I enjoy staying at home. I think it's the best way to relax.

v.s: There was once a little girl who lived in a village. She had a good friend called Lisa. One day, Lisa said to the little girl, 'If I give you three wishes, what will you wish for?' The little girl thought for a moment and said, 'First, I wish that my mother would recover from her illness. Second, I wish that my father would find a good job. And third, I wish that my family would be happy forever.'

Lisa was surprised. She said, 'You are very kind. Most people would ask for wealth or beauty. But you are different. You care about your family more than yourself.' The little girl smiled and said, 'I know. But my family's happiness is my happiness.'

a.s: Jimmy is a young boy who studies English with his friend, Lucy. In this lesson, we learn about the past simple tense and how to use it to describe actions that have already finished. We also learn some new vocabulary related to daily activities and emotions.

v.s: Dear teacher, Many thanks for the wonderful party you gave us last Friday night.
We enjoyed it very much. It was a great success.
We like your delicious dishes and drinks.
We had a good time there.
Thank you again! And best wishes to you.
This tense is used to talk about actions that have already finished. It is formed by adding -ed to the end of regular verbs, or using the past form of irregular verbs.
Words such as party, enjoy, success, delicious, dish, drink, and time are commonly used when talking about social gatherings and the experience of attending them.
